			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2008</a> paper:</span><br><i>Transformation Language Integration Based on Profiles and Higher Order Transformations</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/PieterVanGorp.html">Pieter Van Gorp</a>, <a href="../profile/AnneKeller.html">Anne Keller</a>, <a href="../profile/DirkJanssens.html">Dirk Janssens</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-00434-6_14">10.1007/978-3-642-00434-6_14</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagM">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> Its core is integrating multiple transformation languages via profiles and higher-order transformations.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3b.html"><span class="tagL">T3B: Transformation Languages</span></a><ul><li> It deals directly with transformation languages as first-class artifacts that must be composed/integrated.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4b.html"><span class="tagL">T4B: Horizontal Transformation</span></a><ul><li> Higher-order transformations and profiles are used as transformation mechanisms for integration.
</li></ul></li></ul>
